Write the overlap integral for the two hybrids  

\[
S_{ab}= \int \psi_a^{*}\,\psi_b\,d\tau
      =\frac{1}{4}\int 
        (-\phi_{2s}+\phi_{2p_x}+\phi_{2p_y}+\phi_{2p_z})
        (-\phi_{2s}-\phi_{2p_x}-\phi_{2p_y}+\phi_{2p_z})\,d\tau .
\]

Expand the product inside the integral, keeping each term separate:

\[
\frac{1}{4}\int \Big[ 
   (\phi_{2s})^{2}
 +\phi_{2s}\phi_{2p_x}
 +\phi_{2s}\phi_{2p_y}
 +\phi_{2s}\phi_{2p_z}
 -\phi_{2p_x}\phi_{2s}
 -(\phi_{2p_x})^{2}
 -\phi_{2p_x}\phi_{2p_y}
 -\phi_{2p_x}\phi_{2p_z}
 -\phi_{2p_y}\phi_{2s}
 -\phi_{2p_y}\phi_{2p_x}
 -(\phi_{2p_y})^{2}
 -\phi_{2p_y}\phi_{2p_z}
 +\phi_{2p_z}\phi_{2s}
 +\phi_{2p_z}\phi_{2p_x}
 +\phi_{2p_z}\phi_{2p_y}
 +(\phi_{2p_z})^{2}
 \Big] d\tau .
\]

Because the atomic orbitals form an orthonormal set,

\[
\int \phi_i\,\phi_j\,d\tau = 
\begin{cases}
1 & (i=j)\\
0 & (i\neq j)
\end{cases}.
\]

Thus every integral containing two different orbitals vanishes, while the four integrals of squares each equal 1. The surviving terms are therefore

\[
S_{ab}= \frac{1}{4}\big[\,1 - 1 - 1 + 1\,\big].
\]

Carrying out the arithmetic gives \(S_{ab}=0\). Hence the two hybrid orbitals ψ_a and ψ_b are orthogonal.

